<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:department>Institute of Child Health</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/1E2C2EF9-3574-4A95-977D-FB13F5C835A8"><gtr:id>1E2C2EF9-3574-4A95-977D-FB13F5C835A8</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Lorna</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Frances</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Halliday</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE012256%2F1"><gtr:id>7D523D81-1B39-442A-9605-246C777D947F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Are auditory processing deficits linked to literacy problems? A comparison of specific reading disability and mild to moderate hearing loss.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E012256/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>It has been known for some time that severe hearing losses that have their onset in childhood often lead to substantial delays in language learning. However, there is evidence to suggest that even subtle deficits in a person?s ability to process sounds might be linked to language-learning problems. For instance, children with language-learning impairments (LLI) such as specific language impairment and dyslexia have been shown to have difficulty discriminating fine differences between sounds. In this programme of research three approaches will be used to explore the link between auditory processing and language-learning. First, behavioural methods will be used to assess the development of auditory processing skills from child- to adulthood in individuals with LLI. Second, electrophysiological recordings will be used to look for differences in the brain processing of sounds between children with LLI and typically-developing children. Finally, the performance of children with LLI on these measures will be compared to that of children with mild to moderate hearing loss. These approaches will be used to assess (a) whether children with LLI show impaired performance on measures of auditory processing, (b) reasons for these impairments, and (c) whether these impairments are causally linked to difficulty with learning to speak/read.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-11-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>87775</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This project examined the link between auditory processing and developmental disorders of language. In a large-scale sample of children (7-14 years) and adults with language-learning impairments (n = 96) we found evidence for deficits in performance on behavioural measures of auditory processing (frequency discrimination and frequency modulation detection) relative to age-matched controls. These deficits could not be explained by differences in auditory or non-auditory maturation, sensory or nonsensory attention, or nonverbal intelligence. In a follow-up study using event-related potential (ERP) methodology, a subset of these children (n = 20) showed a different pattern of brain responses to a passive auditory discrimination task (frequency oddball) relative to controls. However, structural equation modelling and comparison with a group of children with mild to moderate hearing loss, independently suggest that deficits in auditory processing are not causally linked to literacy problems. The results challenge existing theories that claim that developmental language disorders such as dyslexia arise from low-level deficits in auditory processing.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The results may be used by teachers, speech and language therapists, and audiologists, in informing their practice regarding the treatment of auditory processing deficits in children. The results from this project indicate that many children (and indeed some adults) with language-learning impairments such as dyslexia experience deficits in processing auditory information. Whilst these do not appear to have a direct causal influence in the development of language difficulties, they may lead to additional difficulties for this group in complex listening environments (e.g. speech in noise). Auditory training may offer some method of improving the auditory processing deficits of this population.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>240E07D1-A659-44AA-BCAD-F8F8D2161D19</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-3369628250.011828b2effd78</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Education,Healthcare</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>A1128C0B-52F4-4F20-8A2A-173673D33304</gtr:id><gtr:title>Oxford Handbook of Auditory Science: Ear, The Auditory Brain, Hearing</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/dd5ee41a6cb827161aba4a218bf7de45"><gtr:id>dd5ee41a6cb827161aba4a218bf7de45</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Halliday, L. F., &amp; Moore, D. R.</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780199581412</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>i-7766921872.0560163b874048</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>93126A8D-82F0-498E-A5AA-18F0A38B4338</gtr:id><gtr:title>Use of auditory learning to manage listening problems in children.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Philosophical transactions of the Royal Society of London. Series B, Biological sciences</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/760090565cb4f49c4dbc3a2438be4a16"><gtr:id>760090565cb4f49c4dbc3a2438be4a16</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Moore DR</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2009-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0962-8436</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>pm_53cbf8cbf8c8063cb</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>4DA30958-85B0-4207-AE29-ED477B87AC10</gtr:id><gtr:title>Lack of generalization of auditory learning in typically developing children.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of speech, language, and hearing research : JSLHR</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/aad2292f71bf3e3331